Comments Based on plot defining characteristics of the cluster

Cluster1 : -mix of socioeconomic class -consist of a high number of family members -have high total volume, volume per transaction, and value -they purchase different brand for a different product -dont look for any promotions for purchase -volume purchased under price category 2,4 are high -dont follow any suggestion for purchase

Cluster2 : -have low socioeconomic class -high transaction per brand -high volume per transaction volume -have loyalty towards a brand -have purchased based on price category 3 -purchase product proposition category 14 -not keen on purchasing product based on promotions

cluster 3: - have a group of people with high socioeconomic class - education level is high - high value of durable possessed hence they have an average price as high - loyal to other 999 products - look for promotion of at least 6% -volume purchased under price category 1 are high - purchase product proposition category 6,7,8,10,12,13

  1. Develop a model that classifies the data into these segments. Since this information would most likely be used in targeting direct-mail promotions, it would be useful to select a market segment that would be defined as a success in the classification model. comments here we are using cluster 1 as a base to target our promotional offer since they have 50% of the data point can be used to find characteristics for building model
subset402<- subset40 ##
subset402$clusters<-as.factor( ifelse((subset402$clusters==2) | (subset402$clusters==3), "No","Yes"))

traindata <- subset402[c(1:500),]
testdata <- subset402[c(501:600),]

model402 <- glm(clusters~.,data = traindata,family = binomial(link='logit') )
## Warning: glm.fit: fitted probabilities numerically 0 or 1 occurred
summary(model402)
